We inherently thought that the decision was somewhat biased as he spent most of his time giving credit to Gateway's content when giving their feedback and we only received the above statement.

Our adjudicator was very good in this round and she gave us excellent feedback. Also she allowed us to ask questions and gave us detailed answers.

First of all , she said in her feedback our side the one that provided the definitions, the framework of the motion and as for my question she admitted that there were no definitions that were presented by the other side and as a debater I think that if the other side is not even providing the definitions of the motion , should not be able to win a debate at the first place and also in her feedback she clearly mentioned that the other side had the clear framework but I don’t think if it’s not including the actual keywords that they are arguing for how could that be a clear framework and also she mentioned that she googled a term (concept ) that was presented by the other side and she made assumptions on that and also I don’t think it’s the actual duty of a adjudicator to get an outside resource, information and support a team’s case , if the side that was unable to present the concept in a way that the adjudicator could understand it in the first place that should be a failure of the explanation itself of the side that presented it

All arguments placed by the losing side was taken out of context and when given the ballet she was taking her own personal belief and understanding unto her decision making. Throughout the debate we were really confident to win but she said that the winning side won by a *landslide*. Greatly disappointed by the fact that the judgmaking was biased. She also mentioned that we were not *confident* and all our points were *vague* even though we were really positive on our points. She at one point was praising one of the speakers from the winning side for being sick but completing her argument even though emotional sympathy should not affect the judge making. The metrics used to compare the two sides wasn't exactly accurate, or well-justified. She said both sides were lacking with POIs in the 2nd half, but this was largely because we didn't have any content to ask POIs due to a lack of case building on the other side - and when we did ask a POI in the 1st half, they didn't even answer it all. Also, it was slightly confusing to keep track of which side she was reffering to, because she kept on saying '"you guys"", when there were clear differences between our two cases. Moreover, I also think that her saying new content was brought out later on in debate was not justified, because she pointed to something that we mentioned in O3, when in fact it was specifically mentioned in O2 - however this isn't a major problem for our case.

tournament.motion: This House opposes the stigma against laziness

This house prefers historical media that focuses on the experiences of ordinary people (All Quiet on the Western Front, The Help, Les Miserable) rather than media that focuses on the lives of great figures and important leaders of society (Napoleon, Oppenheimer, Malcolm X)

This house would end the relationship before your partner leaves

You are a middle-class Sri Lankan who is about to enter a government university. You are also in a committed, fulfilling relationship with your first love, but your partner will be going overseas for their higher education and will not be able to meet you for a long period of time. Your partner has expressed that they wish to continue your relationship long distance and has said that they plan on returning to Sri Lanka once their higher education is complete

This house prefers a world where professional sports adopt a rookie draft rather than a free agency model

A rookie draft is a process by which teams select players who are new to the league, such as high school or college prospects.

Teams generally pick in reverse order, with the least successful team from the previous season receiving the first pick. During the draft, rookies do not have a choice in which team they join. The league typically regulates the rookie’s contract length and salary, which can vary depending on their draft position (e.g., 1st round pick, 2nd round pick). Examples of leagues with a rookie draft system include the NBA and the NFL.

In contrast, a free agency model allows new athletes to negotiate their contracts directly with any interested teams, with minimal interference from the league. Examples of leagues with a free agency model include the MLB and NHL.

This House Supports the use of extraction rights to natural resources as a form of collateral for external debt held by governments

Extraction rights refers to the set of rights government may grant different actors; to extract, use and/or sell their natural resources; including, but not limited to, minerals, natural gas, ores, metals, water, etc.

This house believes that developing countries should drop local languages (Tamil/Hindi in India, Urdu in Pakistan, Bengali in Bangladesh) in favor of English as the primary medium of instruction in schools
This house believes that social movements should use the courts rather than the legislature to advance social change

THW require all isolated communities to give all 18-year-olds a 'Rumspringa'

Rumspringa is a mandatory Amish rite of passage that entails sending off 18-year-olds to live in the outside world for 1 year, after which they may choose to return to the community or continue to live in the outside world. In exchange for preserving this rite of passage the Amish are often granted significant control and autonomy over their lifestyle and community practices (homeschooling, legal protection for religious practices etc.)

THBT democratic states with growing economies (Brazil, India, Indonesia, Bangladesh, Kenya) should attempt to develop closer economic, political and military ties with China at the expense of closer ties with the US

This house believes that postcolonial states, when developing their cultural and national identity (lifestyle, political discourse, history curriculums, anthems, street names, holidays, flag, national heroes etc.) should prioritize pre-colonial history and notions of indigeneity over themes of anti-colonial resistance.
